Code  :
def list_sort(items):
    """Write a routine that accepts a collection of text items,
    removes entries whose lengths are odd,
    and returns the resulting sequence in a sorted form,
    The input will be textual rather than numeric,
    and duplicates may occur.
    The ordering should be increasing by the length of each item; sort according to that.
    When items share the same length, use alphabetical ordering as a tie-breaker.
    The routine should return a collection of texts arranged per these rules.
    You may assume that some items can have the same length.
    For example:
    assert list_sort(["aa", "a", "aaa"]) => ["aa"]
    assert list_sort(["ab", "a", "aaa", "cd"]) => ["ab", "cd"]
    """
    # Filter out items with odd lengths
    items = [item for item in items if len(item) % 2 == 0]

    # Sort the items by length and then alphabetically
    items.sort(key=lambda x: (len(x), x))

    return items
